<%def .StyleGuideLink>
<a id="capguide-<% $_[0] %>" href="#capguide-<% $_[0] %>"><b>&lowast;</b></a>
</%def>

<p><b>Capitalization Guide for Submitting/Editing Data</b></p>

<p>
	<& .StyleGuideLink, "general" &>
	Use the following standard guidelines for capitalizing titles (releases,
	songs) in the English language. <b>A more detailed description of these
	rules and guidelines for other languages can be found on the
	<a href="http://wiki.musicbrainz.org/wiki.pl?CapitalizationStandard">CapitalizationStandard</a> wiki page.</b>
</p>
<p>
	All titles should be in standard mixed case (initial caps and following
	lower case), as noted below:
</p>

<ol class="StyleGuideList">

	<li>
		<& .StyleGuideLink, "first-and-last" &>
		Always capitalize the first and last word of a title. If a title
    is broken up by major punctuation (colon, question mark, exclamation
    mark, em-dash, parentheses, or quotes), treat each distinct piece
    of the title as a whole, and always capitalize the first and last
    words of each division.
	</li>
	<li>
		<& .StyleGuideLink, "exceptions" &>
		Capitalize all words between the first and last word of a title except:
    <ol type="a">
			<li>Articles: <b>a</b>, <b>an</b>, <b>the</b></li>
			<li>Coordinate conjunctions: <b>and</b>, <b>but</b>, <b>or</b>, <b>nor</b></li>
			<li>Short (three letters or less) prepositions: <b>as</b>, <b>at</b>, <b>by</b>,
				<b>for</b>, <b>in</b>, <b>of</b>, <b>on</b>, <b>to</b>
				&mdash; except when used as adverbs or as an inseparable
				part of a verb</li>
			<li>When used to form an infinitive: <b>to</b></li>
		</ol>
	</li>
	<li>
		<& .StyleGuideLink, "hyphens" &>
		In compounds formed by hyphens, capitalize each part except where
    the part would not be capitalized if it were a separate word.
	</li>
	<li>
		<& .StyleGuideLink, "abbr" &>
		Only use all caps for acronyms or abbreviations where common use
    is all caps.
	</li>
	<li>
		<& .StyleGuideLink, "contractions" &>
		Capitalize contractions and slang consistent with the rules above
    to the extent that such clearly apply. For example, do not capitalize
    <b>o</b>' for "<b>of</b>", '<b>n</b>' or <b>n</b>' for "<b>and</b>".
	</li>
</ol>
